The shrine is located in the eastern part of Fujieda City, at the center of the Okabe Town Miwa area.
According to tradition, Miwa Shrine was founded in the 3rd year of the reign of {{ill|Empress Kōgyoku|ja|皇極天皇|12=draft}} (644). During an epidemic in the eastern provinces, the shrine was established to pray for the disease’s retreat. It is said to have been founded as a branch of {{ill|Ōmiwa Shrine|ja|大神神社|12=draft}} in {{ill|Yamato Province|ja|Yamato Province|12=draft}} (modern-day Nara Prefecture). The shrine is recorded as a {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|12=draft}}, making it an ancient and historically significant shrine.<ref name="engi">[http://engishiki.org/suruga/bun/sr130101-01.html Miwa Shrine] - Engishiki Shrine Research</ref><ref name="genbu">[https://genbu.net/data/suruga/miwa_title.htm Miwa Shrine] - Genbu</ref>
In the 6th year of {{ill|Meiji era|ja|明治|12=draft}} (1873), the shrine was ranked as a {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|12=draft}}. Later, in the 40th year of Meiji (1907), it was designated as a {{ill|Shinzen heihakuryō kyoshinsha|ja|神饌幣帛料供進社|12=draft}}, a shrine authorized to receive state offerings.<ref name="engi"/>
== deity ==
* {{ill|Ōmononushi|ja|大物主神|12=draft}}
